{{Italic title}}
{{Infobox document
|document_name = ''Famuli vestrae pietatis''
|image = 
|date_created = 494
|writer = [[Pope Gelasius I]]
|purpose = Expressed the Gelasian doctrine
}}
'''''{{lang|la|Famuli vestrae pietatis}}''''', also known by the Latin mnemonic '''''{{lang|la|duo sunt}}''''' ("there are two"), is a letter written in 494 by [[Pope Gelasius I]] to [[Byzantine Emperor]] [[Anastasius I Dicorus]] which expressed the Gelasian doctrine.{{sfnm|1a1=Bjork|1y=2010|2a1=Denzinger|2y=2012|2loc=n. 347}} According to commentary in the ''[[Enchiridion symbolorum]]'', the letter is "the most celebrated document of the [[ancient Church]] concerning the two powers on earth."{{sfn|Denzinger|2012|p=121}} The Gelasian doctrine articulates a Christian theology about division of authority and power. All Medieval theories about division of power between priestly spiritual authority and secular temporal authority were versions of the Gelasian doctrine.{{sfn|Strawn|2015}} According to the Gelasian doctrine, secular temporal authority is inferior to priestly spiritual authority since a priestly spiritual authority is responsible for the eternal condition of both a secular temporal authority and the subjects of that secular temporal authority but "implies that the priestly authority is inferior to the secular authority in the secular domain."{{sfn|Strawn|2015}}

==Biblical foundation==
[[Paul of Tarsus]] taught that [[Jesus]] was the successor of [[Melchizedek]].{{refn|{{bibleref2|Hebrews|5:6|NRSVCE}}, {{bibleref2-nb|Hebrews|5:10|NRSVCE}}, {{bibleref2-nb|Hebrews|6:20|NRSVCE}}, {{bibleref2-nb|Hebrews|7:1|NRSVCE}}, {{bibleref2-nb|Hebrews|7:10-11|NRSVCE}}, {{bibleref2-nb|Hebrews|7:15|NRSVCE}}, {{bibleref2-nb|Hebrews|7:17|NRSVCE}}, {{bibleref2-nb|Hebrews|7:21|NRSVCE}}, cited in {{harvtxt|Strawn|2015}}.}}

Jesus taught [[Render unto Caesar|submission to the power of two independent authorities]],{{refn|{{bibleref2|Matthew|22:21|NRSVCE}}, cited in {{harvtxt|Strawn|2015}}.}} Paul explained that everyone is subject to the God instituted authority of government which includes taxation.{{refn|{{bibleref2|Romans|13:1-7|NRSVCE}}, cited in {{harvtxt|Strawn|2015}}.}}

==Dualistic principle of Church and State==
This letter established the dualistic principle that would underlie all Western European political thought for almost a [[millennium]]. Gelasius expressed a distinction between two principles governing the world, which Gelasius called the "sacred authority of bishops" (''{{lang|la|auctoritas sacrata pontificum}}'') and the "royal power" (''{{lang|la|regalis potestas}}'').{{sfn|Denzinger|2012|loc=n. 347}}

==''Potestas'' and ''auctoritas''==
These two principles, ''{{lang|la|[[auctoritas]]}}'' lending justification to ''{{lang|la|[[potestas]]}}'', and ''{{lang|la|potestas}}'' providing the executive strength for ''{{lang|la|auctoritas}}'' were, Gelasius said, to be considered independent in their own spheres of operation, yet expected to work together in harmony.

==Sovereign immunity==
{{citation needed span|text=The letter played a significant role in the development of the legal doctrine of [[sovereign immunity]], in that it gave political protections to the papacy and the monarchy,who promised not to violate each other's respective jurisdictions.|date=February 2016}} This doctrine remains in force in international politics, even though most absolute monarchies have been replaced by constitutional monarchies or republics.

